@baseUrl = http://localhost:8000
@accessToken = {{login.response.body.access_token}}

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Sound Necklace — /api/sound-necklace
#
# Every resource is implemented: sessions, the audio bucket, the artifacts, the voice
# answers and the advisory editor lock. Nothing answers 501 any more. The emitted OpenAPI
# is the contract the SPA generates its TypeScript types from:
#
#   # with the app running (uvicorn app.main:app):
#   npx openapi-typescript@7 http://localhost:8000/openapi.json -o sound-necklace-types.ts
#
#   # or straight from a dumped schema, no server needed:
#   uv run python -c "import json; from app.main import app; print(json.dumps(app.openapi()))" > openapi.json
#   npx openapi-typescript@7 openapi.json -o sound-necklace-types.ts
#
# Every schema in this module is marked `x-stability: experimental` (provisional
# until each resource finalizes its shape). The acousteme envelope is now concrete:
# `{codebook_version, hop_sec, granularity_frames}`, and beadSec = frames[level] × hop_sec.
# It is null for an audio with no servable grid — a fallback, not an error (PRD §6.1).
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

### Login (sets the bearer token for the requests below)
# @name login
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "facilitator@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}

### Sessions: list
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Sessions: create
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "audio_id": "aud_1",
  "project_id": "prj_1",
  "story_name": "O Conto do Boto",
  "story_slug": "conto-do-boto",
  "granularity_level": "medium",
  "bead_sec": 0.5,
  "manifest_id": "fnv1a32:d31a8419",
  "pipeline_consent": true
}

### Sessions: fetch one (meta only — the state has its own route below)
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Sessions: autosave the state envelope (unconditional — what the SPA's autosaver does)
# The request body IS the state document. It is stored as the exact bytes sent and
# served back unchanged: the SPA re-validates it under a strict schema, so anything
# the API re-serialized would come back as an unresumable session.
# The response carries the new version in `ETag`.
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/state
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "schema_version": 1,
  "mode": "triagem",
  "beadSec": 0.5,
  "whole": { "id": "S1", "span": { "s": 0, "e": 23 }, "confirmed": true }
}

### Sessions: autosave with the version guard (two machines on the same session)
# `If-Match` is the version from the last ETag. If someone else saved in the meantime
# the write is refused with 409 and the body carries `current_version` to reload from.
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/state
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}
Content-Type: application/json
If-Match: "3"

{
  "schema_version": 1,
  "mode": "mapeamento",
  "beadSec": 0.5,
  "whole": { "id": "S1", "span": { "s": 0, "e": 23 }, "confirmed": true }
}

### Sessions: resume — the saved document, byte for byte (ETag = current version)
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/state
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Sessions: complete (no body — the artifacts go to the artifacts route)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/complete
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Sessions: reopen a completed session
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/reopen
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Lock: acquire / renew (one route — they are the same operation)
# The client heartbeats this every 15s against a 60s lease. Idempotent for the holder.
# Losing is NOT an error: a session held by someone else answers 200 with THEIR name, and
# the SPA opens in review mode off it —
#   {"held": true, "holder": {"user_id": "u_2", "display_name": "Alice"},
#    "expires_at": "2026-07-17T10:31:00+00:00"}
# Exactly those three keys, always. The SPA parses this under z.strictObject, so a fourth
# key throws on the client — and the app shell swallows that throw together with the
# autosave wiring behind it. The fencing counter is server-side only for this reason.
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/lock
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Lock: who holds it (the review-mode gate reads this on open)
# Unheld, or held by a lease that has lapsed, both read as:
#   {"held": false, "holder": null, "expires_at": null}
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/lock
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Lock: release (the SPA calls this on unload)
# 204 always: releasing a lease that lapsed, that another tab took, or that never existed
# is a no-op. Only ever releases your own — a stale tab cannot unlock the current holder.
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/lock
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Lock: what a fenced write looks like (by a non-holder)
# Fenced: PUT /state, POST /complete, POST /reopen, POST /artifacts. NOT fenced: the
# voice /resources routes — ENG-264 left that guard out deliberately and tightening it is
# its own issue.
# The holder is the bearer's user, not a per-tab token — the SPA sends no token anywhere.
# So this only bites while somebody ELSE holds a live lease; an unlocked session autosaves
# exactly as it always did. 409 with:
#   {"detail": "This session is being edited by Alice.", "code": "SESSION_LOCKED",
#    "holder_name": "Alice", "expires_at": "2026-07-17T10:31:00+00:00"}
#
# Two different 409s live on PUT /state and `code` is what tells them apart:
#   CONFLICT       → your copy is stale; body carries current_version; reload and retry
#   SESSION_LOCKED → someone else is editing; stop writing and open in review
# A caller who is both locked out AND stale gets SESSION_LOCKED: telling them to reload
# and retry would loop forever.

### Consent: record one, or re-confirm it (§12 / O6)
# The record is the authoritative evidence of the lawful basis. The `pipeline_consent`
# boolean on the session is write-only — the SPA sends it on create and then reads its own
# copy out of the state document; no response carries it. Recording a consent keeps that
# boolean in step so the two cannot disagree, but the record is what to read.
#
# `type` is the whole body. Who confirmed it is the bearer and when is the server's clock
# — neither is the client's to assert. Idempotent per (session, type): re-confirming
# updates the record and its timestamp instead of opening a second one, and 201 either way.
#
# Two types, and they are two different speakers:
#   pipeline_use  → the facilitator attests the story may be processed
#   voice_answers → the listener consents to their own voice being recorded (§8.7 records
#                   21+ files of it). The listener holds no account, so `confirmed_by` is
#                   the facilitator who WITNESSED it — the witness, never the subject.
#
# Creating a session with `pipeline_consent: true` already records the pipeline_use one,
# in the same transaction. `false` records nothing at all: absent, denied and granted are
# three different claims and only the last is a consent.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/consent
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "type": "pipeline_use"
}

### Consent: what is held for this session
# An empty list is not an error — it is a session for which no consent was recorded.
# The oral form §12 admits (a consent audio for a speaker who cannot sign) will read back
# here once an upload route fills it — it is a nullable column on our own table, added with
# that route rather than shipped empty ahead of it.
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/consent
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Artifacts: upload the three on completion (RAW bytes — byte-identical custody)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/artifacts
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=----boundary

------boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="manifest"; filename="manifesto-contas.json"
Content-Type: application/json

< ./manifesto-contas.json
------boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="anchoring"; filename="retorno-ancoragem.json"
Content-Type: application/json

< ./retorno-ancoragem.json
------boundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="report"; filename="relatorio-mapeamento.md"
Content-Type: text/markdown

< ./relatorio-mapeamento.md
------boundary--

### Artifacts: download one (redirects to a signed URL — audit point)
# 307 to a short-TTL signed GET; storage serves the bytes verbatim and the API never
# proxies them, which is what keeps the download byte-identical to the upload. The
# frozen filename (PRD §10) rides in the object key, so the browser saves
# `retorno-ancoragem.json` without the API touching a byte. ENG-266 hooks here.
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/artifacts/anchoring
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Bucket: list a project's audios
# The audios a project may see, each with its acousteme envelope and collection consent.
# The bindings are seeded per project:
#   uv run python scripts/seed_sn_audio_refs.py --project-id <uuid> [--consent]
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/projects/prj_1/audios
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Bucket: short-TTL signed URL for an audio (audit point)
# The bytes live in a private bucket and are never proxied, so this is where the Sound
# Necklace reaches them — and where ENG-266 will hook its audit log.
#
# The only path in this API — but only since ENG-290. GET /api/oc/acoustemes/{id}/audio
# used to mint the same signed URL for the same object behind nothing but
# get_current_user (no app role, no project scoping); it is retired.
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/audios/ruth-a-historia-de-rute/url
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Voice answers: upload one to its canonical path (raw WebM bytes, replace on re-record)
# The path is a fixed allowlist — respostas/level{1,2,3}/…/<k>.webm — validated before it
# names the object, so no traversal and no free-form key can reach storage.
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/resources?path=respostas/level1/recontar.webm
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}
Content-Type: audio/webm

< ./recontar.webm

### Voice answers: which questions are answered (the Mapeamento screen reads this)
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/resources
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Voice answers: short-TTL signed URL to play one back (audit point)
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/resources/url?path=respostas/level1/recontar.webm
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

### Voice answers: delete one (object + row; a path never recorded is a no-op)
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/api/sound-necklace/sessions/sess_1/resources?path=respostas/level1/recontar.webm
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}
